2026-06-17 16:00:04 | DEBUG    | openai._base_client  | Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/deployments/text-embedding-3-small/embeddings', 'headers': {'api-key': '<redacted>'}, 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-c5f8b8c7-869c-4074-8f26-21270dc3a043', 'post_parser': <function Embeddings.create.<locals>.parser at 0x0000017A2C0D19B0>, 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'input': ['2 6.', 'Similarly, the velocities acquired by other electrons in the conductor will be 2 2 2 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 3 3 3 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 ....., n n n v u a .', '\x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 7.', 'The average velocity of all the free electrons in the conductor under the effect of external electric field is the drift velocity d v\x01  of the free electrons.', 'Thus, 2 n d v v ...', 'v v n \x02 \x02 \x02 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 1 2 2 n n u a u a ...', 'u a n \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 2 n 1 2 n ...', 'u u ...', 'u a n n \x04 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x05 \x06 \x01 \x02 \x07 \x08 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 0 a a \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x04 \x01 \x01 where, 2 n ...', 'n \x04 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x04 \x01 = average time that has elapsed since each electron suffered its last collision with the ion/ atom of conductor and is called average relaxation time.', '8.', 'Its value is the order of 10 –14 second.', '9.', 'Putting the value of a\x01  in the above relation, we have d eE v m \x03 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 Average drift speed, d eE v m \x01 \x04 The negative sign show that d v\x01  is opposite to the direction of E \x01 .', '3.1 Relaxation time (\x04 \x04 \x04 \x04 ) The time interval between two successive collisions of electrons with the positive ions in the metallic lattice is defined as relaxation time rms mean free path r.m.s.', 'velocity of electrons v \x04 \x01 \x01 .', 'With rise in temperature vrms increases consequently \x04 decreases.', '3.2   Mobility Drift velocity per unit electric field is called mobility of electron i.e.', 'd v E \x01 It’s unit is 2 m volt sec \x03 \x01 If cross-section is constant, I \x0e J i.e.', 'for a given cross-sectional area, greater the current density, larger will be current.', '\x01 The drift velocity of electrons is small because of the frequent collisions suffered by electrons.', '\x01 The small value of drift velocity produces a large amount of electric current, due to the presence of extremely large number of free electrons in a conductor.', 'The propagation of current is almost at the speed of light and involves electromagnetic process.', 'It is due to this reason that the electric bulb glows immediately when switch is on.', '\x01 In the absence of electric field, the paths of electrons between successive collisions are straight line while in presence of electric field the paths are generally curved.', '\x01 Free electron density in a metal is given by A N x d n A \x01 where NA = Avogrado number, x = number of free electrons per atom, d = density of metal and A = Atomic weight of metal.', '1.', 'Mobility of charge carrier ( ), responsible for current is defined as the magnitude of drift velocity of charge per unit electic filed applied, i.e., d v drift velocity q E / m q electric field E E m \x04 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 2.', 'Mobility of electron, e e e e m \x04 \x01 3.', 'The total current in the conducting material is the sum of the currents due to positive current carriers and negative current carriers.', 'd e v E \x01 4.', 'SI unit of mobility is m 2S –1V –1 or ms –1 N –1 C 3.3  Relation between current and Drift Velocity 1.', 'Consider a conductor (say a copper wire) of length l and of uniform area of cross-section \x0f Volume of the conductor = Al.', '2.', 'If n is the number density of electrons, i.e., the number of free electrons perunit volume of the conductor, then total number of free electrons in the conducture = Aln.', '3.', 'Then total charge on all the free electrons in the conductor, q A ne \x01 \x02 4.', 'The electric field set up across the conductor is given by E = V/l (in magnitude) 5.', 'Due to this field, the free electrons present in the conductor will begin to move with a drift velocity vd towards the left hand side as shown in figure JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev.', 'Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2'], 'model': 'text-embedding-3-small', 'encoding_format': 'base64'}}
