sed quartz = maximum \x1a 1016 \x19-m ) \x1b \x1b \x1b insulator alloy semi-conductor conductor (Maximum for fused quartz) (Minimum for silver \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 \x17 (v) Resistivity depends on the temperature.', 'For metals ) 1( 0 t t \x11 \x02 \x01 \x17 \x17 i.e.', 'resitivity increases with temperature.', '(vi) Resistivity increases with impurity and mechanical stress.', '(vii) Magnetic field increases the resistivity of all metals except iron, cobalt and nickel.', '(viii) Resistivity of certain substances like selenium, cadmium, sulphides is inversely proportional to intensity of light falling upon them.', '3.', 'We have, 2 2 V m m R I A Ane ne \x01 \x01 \x01 \x18 \x04 \x04 \x02 \x02 comparing the above relation with the relation, R A \x01 \x17 \x02 .', '4.', 'We have, the resistivity of the material of a conductor, 2 m ne \x17 \x01 \x04 5.3 Conductivity Reciprocal of resistivity is called conductivity ( ) i.e.', '1 \x01 \x17 with unit mho/m and dimensions ] [ 2 3 3 1 A T L M \x03 \x03 .', '5.4 Conductance Reciprocal of resistance is known as conductance.', '1 C R \x01 It’s unit is 1 \x19  or \x19–1 or “Siemen”.', '5.5  Stretching of Wire If a conducting wire stretches, it’s length increases, area of cross- section decreases so resistance increases but volume remain constant.', 'Suppose for a conducting wire before stretching it’s length = l1, area of cross–section = A1, radius = r1, diameter = d1, and resistance = 1 1 1 l R A \x01 \x17 JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev.', 'Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2'], 'model': 'text-embedding-3-small', 'encoding_format': 'base64'}}
