2026-06-17 16:00:20 | DEBUG    | openai._base_client  | Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/deployments/text-embedding-3-small/embeddings', 'headers': {'api-key': '<redacted>'}, 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-cc6d281b-4103-49b0-aa98-78afff1c4715', 'post_parser': <function Embeddings.create.<locals>.parser at 0x0000017A311EFD70>, 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'input': ['17 Close key K and maintain suitable constant current in the potentiometer wire with the help of rheostat Rh.', 'Adjust the position of jockey on the potentiometer wire where if pressed, the galvanometer show no deflection.', 'Let it be when jockey is as J1.', 'Note the length AJ1 (= l1) of the potentiometer wire.', 'Now emf of the cell, \x1f = potential difference across the length l1 of the potentiometer wire.', 'or = Kl1 ...(1) where K is the potential gradient across the wire.', 'Close key K1 and take out suitable resistance R from the resistance box in the cell circuit.', 'Again find the position of the jockey on the potentiometer wire where galvanometer shows no deflection.', 'Let it be at J2.', 'Note the length of the wire AJ2 ( = l2 say).', 'As current is being drawn from the cell, its terminal potential difference V is balanced and not emf .', 'Therefore, potential difference between two poles of the cell, V = potential difference across the length l2 of the potentiometer wire i.e.', 'V = Kl2 ...(2) Dividing (1) by (2), we have 1 2 V \x01 \x02 \x02 ...(3) We know that the internal resistance r of a cell of emf \x1f, when a resistance R is connected in its circuit is given by V r R 1 R V V \x03 \x05 \x06 \x01 \x18 \x01 \x03 \x07 \x08 ...(4) Putting the value (3) in (4), we get 1 1 2 2 2 r 1 R R \x05 \x06 \x03 \x01 \x03 \x01 \x18 \x07 \x08 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x02 \x02 Thus, knowing the values of l1, l2 and R, the internal resistance r of the cell can be determined.', '12.11  Sensitiveness of Potentiometer The sensitiveness of potentiometer means the smallest potential difference that can be measured with its help.', 'The sensitiveness of a potentiometer can be increased by decreasing its potential gradient.', 'The same can be achieved.', '(i) By increasing the length of potentiometer wire.', '(ii) If the potentiometer wire is of fixed length, the potential gradient can be decreased by reducing the current in the potentiometer wire circuit with the help of rheostat and using a single cell.', 'Difference between Potentiometer and Voltmeter Potentiometer Voltmere 1.', 'It measures the emf of 1.', 'It measures the emf of a a cell very accurately.', 'cell approximately.', '2.', 'While measuring emf it 2.', 'While measuring emf, it does not draw any current drws some current from from the source of the source of emf.', 'known emf.', '3.', 'While measuring emf, 3.', 'While measuring emf the the resistance of poten- resistance of voltmeter is tiometer becomes infinite.', 'high but finite.', '4.', 'Its sensitivity is high.', '4.', 'Its sensitivity is low.', '5.', 'It is based on null 5.', 'It is based on deflection deflection method.', 'method.', '6.', 'It can be used for 6.', 'It can be used only to various purposes.', 'measure emf or potential difference.', '13.', 'HEATING EFFECT OF CURRENT When some potential difference V is applied across a resistance R then the work done by the electric field on charge q to flow through the circuit in time t will be W = qV = Vit = i2R 2 V t Joule R \x01 .', 'This work appears as thermal energy in the resistor.', 'Heat produced by the resistance R is 2 2 W Vit i Rt V t H Cal.', 'J 4 2 4 2 4 2R \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 This relation is called joules heating.', 'Some important relations for solving objective questions are as follow : JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev.', 'Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2'], 'model': 'text-embedding-3-small', 'encoding_format': 'base64'}}
