of electrons of charge in one particular direction in a metal conductor, hence no current”.', '“Drift velocity is defined as the average velocity with which the free electrons get drifted towards the positive end of the conductor under the influence of an external electric field applied”.', 'If V is the potential difference applied across the ends of the conductor of length l, the magnitude of electric field set up is Potential difference V E length \x01 \x01 \x02 3.', 'At any instant of time, the velocity acquired by electron having thermal velocity 1u\x01  will be 1 1 1 v u a \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 where 1\x04  is the time elapsed since it has suffered its last collision with ion/atom of the conductor.', 'Similarly, the velocities acquired by other electrons in the conductor will be 2 2 2 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 3 3 3 v u a , \x01 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 ....., n n n v u a .', 'The average velocity of all the free electrons in the conductor under the effect of external electric field is the drift velocity d v\x01  of the free electrons.', 'v v n \x02 \x02 \x02 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 1 2 2 n n u a u a ... u a n \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 2 n 1 2 n ... u u ...', 'n \x04 \x02 \x04 \x02 \x02 \x04 \x04 \x01 = average time that has elapsed since each electron suffered its last collision with the ion/ atom of conductor and is called average relaxation time.', 'Putting the value of a\x01  in the above relation, we have d eE v m \x03 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 Average drift speed, d eE v m \x01 \x04 The negative sign show that d v\x01  is opposite to the direction of E \x01 .', '3.1 Relaxation time (\x04 \x04 \x04 \x04 ) The time interval between two successive collisions of electrons with the positive ions in the metallic lattice is defined as relaxation time rms mean free path r.m.s.', '\x01 The drift velocity of electrons is small because of the frequent collisions suffered by electrons. \x01 The small value of drift velocity produces a large amount of electric current, due to the presence of extremely large number of free electrons in a conductor.', '\x01 In the absence of electric field, the paths of electrons between successive collisions are straight line while in presence of electric field the paths are generally curved.', '\x01 Free electron density in a metal is given by A N x d n A \x01 where NA = Avogrado number, x = number of free electrons per atom, d = density of metal and A = Atomic weight of metal.', 'Mobility of charge carrier ( ), responsible for current is defined as the magnitude of drift velocity of charge per unit electic filed applied, i.e., d v drift velocity q E / m q electric field E E m \x04 \x04 \x01 \x01 \x01 \x01 2.', 'The total current in the conducting material is the sum of the currents due to positive current carriers and negative current carriers.', 'SI unit of mobility is m 2S –1V –1 or ms –1 N –1 C 3.3  Relation between current and Drift Velocity 1.', 'Consider a conductor (say a copper wire) of length l and of uniform area of cross-section \x0f Volume of the conductor = Al.', '2. If n is the number density of electrons, i.e., the number of free electrons perunit volume of the conductor, then total number of free electrons in the conducture = Aln. 3.', 'Due to this field, the free electrons present in the conductor will begin to move with a drift velocity vd towards the left hand side as shown in figure JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev.', 'Time taken by the free electrons to cross the conductors, t = l/vd Hence, current, d q A ne dI t t v \x01 \x01 \x01 \x02 \x02 or d I A n e v \x01 7.', 'OHM’S LAW Ohm’s law states that the current (I) flowing through a conductor is directly proportional to the potential difference (V) across the ends of the conductor”. i.e., I \x0e V or V \x0e I or V = RI or V R constant I \x01 \x01 4.1 Deduction of Ohm’s law We know that d eE v m \x01 \x04 But E = V/l \x0f d e V v m